'''Daniel Mattes''' (born November 14, 1972) is an Austrian internet entrepreneur and business angel. He is the founder and CEO of Artificial Intelligence company 42.cx and a judge and business angel on the Austrian television show '2 Minuten 2 Millionen', the Austrian version of [[Shark Tank]], which airs on Puls4.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prosiebensat1puls4.com/content/beitrag/131030_2m2m_pioneers.html|last= |first= |date=October 30, 2013|publisher=ProSiebenSat.1 PULS 4|accessdate=2014-02-24|title=5 Business Angels vergeben 2 Millionen Euro in der PULS 4 Start-Up-Show. Ab 25. November 2013, immer um 20:15 Uhr, exklusiv auf PULS 4}}</ref>

His 42.cx Center of Excellence for Artificial Intelligence focuses on the commercialization of [[Artificial Intelligence]] ("AI"). The company is based in Vienna, Austria and was incorporated in November 2015.<ref name="Futurezone">{{cite web|url=http://futurezone.at/thema/start-ups/42-neues-ki-start-up-von-jajah-gruender-daniel-mattes/165.491.442|title=42: Neues KI-Start-up von Jajah-Gründer Daniel Mattes|publisher=Futurezone|accessdate=2015-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nachrichten.at/nachrichten/wirtschaft/Internetmillionaer-Mattes-wagt-Versuch-Nummer-3;art15,2038527|title=Internetmillionaer-Mattes-wagt-Versuch-Nummer-3|publisher=Nachrichten|accessdate=2015-11-23}}</ref> Prior to 42.cx, in 2010, he founded [[Jumio]], an online authentication company.

Prior to Jumio, in 2005, he founded [[VoIP]] company [[Jajah]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2006/09/15/technology/disruptors_jajah.biz2/index.htm|last=Schonfeld|first=Erick |author2=Jeanette Borzo|date=September 20, 2006|publisher=Business 2.0|accessdate=2009-02-20|title=Totally free and hassle-free phone calls}}</ref> which was acquired 2009 for $207 million by Telefónica.<ref name="Hetz">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE5BM1H320091223|accessdate=2009-12-23| work=Reuters | first=Robert | last=Hetz | date=2009-12-23|title=Telefonica buys Internet phone provider Jajah}}</ref> In 2007, he was voted 81st most important Austrian citizen by Austrian magazine "News" in the "1000 most important Austrians" list.<ref name="NEWS Magazine 01/2007">{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/35659901@N04/3300709871/sizes/l/|work=NEWS Magazine 01/2007|publisher=NEWS Verlag|language=German|accessdate=2009-02-22|title=Die 1000 wichtigsten Oesterreicher}}</ref>

==Biography==
{{BLP unsourced section|date=June 2012}}
Daniel, oldest child of Edeltraud and Manfred Mattes, grew up in [[Freiburg]], Germany and [[Wels]], Austria.{{cn|date=September 2018}} He has two brothers, Sebastian and Simon.{{cn|date=September 2018}}

He studied Computer Science & Economics at the University of Linz (Austria), received the University diploma "Certified e-Business Manager" from the Danube University Krems (Austria) and did his post-graduate work in [[IT Management]] at the Danube University of Krems (Austria).{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}

==Professional life==

In 2015, Mattes founded ''42.cx Center of Excellence for Artificial Intelligence'', a start-up that focuses on the commercialization of [[Artificial Intelligence]] ("AI"). The company is based in Vienna, Austria and was incorporated in November 2015.<ref name="Futurezone"/>

In 2010, Mattes founded [[Jumio]] Inc., a start-up for online authentication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://microsoft-news.tmcnet.com/news/2010/06/11/4840943.htm|title=Jajah founder unveils online payments start-up Jumio|publisher=tmcnet|accessdate=2010-06-19}}</ref>

In 2005, Mattes, with [[Roman Scharf]] formed [[Jajah]].{{cn|date=September 2018}} Mattes acted as Executive Chairman until 2009.{{cn|date=September 2018}} During this time, they raised $35 million in venture funding from Deutsche Telekom AG, Intel Capital, [[Sequoia Capital]] and Globespan Capital Partners.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2009/12/14/daily96.html|accessdate=2009-12-20|title=Reports: O2 to buy Jajah for $200M | date=2009-12-20}}</ref> After reaching 25 million clients worldwide, Jajah was acquired December 2009 by Telefónica for $207 million in an all-cash deal.<ref name="Hetz"/>

In 1999, Mattes co-founded the e-government solution company "Auftrag.at" with a direct co-ownership of the government owned publication "[[Wiener Zeitung]]". They lobbied to allow public tenders to be published on business websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wien-konkret.at/wirtschaft/printmedien/4/wiener-zeitung-lieferanzeiger/|title=lieferanzeiger.at|publisher=Wien-Konkret|language=German|accessdate=2009-02-20}}</ref> The company received Austria's Federal Award of Excellence in 2002<ref name="fox">{{cite press release | title = Auftrag.at gewinnt "multimedia & e-business Staatspreis" 2002  | publisher = NewsFox | date = September 18, 2002 | url = http://www.newsfox.com/pte.mc?pte=020918044 | accessdate = 2009-02-20}}</ref> and has become the de facto standard for public tenders in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wienerzeitung.at/DesktopDefault.aspx?TabID=4103&Alias=wzo&cob=390256 |title=Zuschlag per Mausklick |last=Dirnbacher |first=Stephanie |date=January 8, 2009 |publisher=Wiener Zeitung |language=German |accessdate=2009-02-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308043335/http://www.wienerzeitung.at/DesktopDefault.aspx?TabID=4103 |archivedate=2009-03-08 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brz.gv.at/Portal.Node/brz/public?gentics.am=PCP&p.contentid=10007.28879|title=PEPPOL (Pan European Public Procurement Online)|date=May 23, 2008|publisher=BRZ Portal|language=German|accessdate=2009-02-20}}</ref>

