{{Infobox person | name = Paul Kangas | image = Pauk kangas.jpg | caption = Kangas in 2011 | birth_name = Paul Henry Kangas | birth_date = {{birth date|1937|04|14}} | birth_place = [[Houghton, Michigan]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|2017|02|28|1937|04|14}} | death_place = [[Miami, Florida]], U.S. | alma_mater = [[University of Michigan]] | occupation = Business broadcaster | spouse = | children = | credits = Co-anchor of ''[[Nightly Business Report]]'' }}
'''Paul Henry Kangas''' (April 14, 1937 – February 28, 2017) was the [[Miami]]-based co-anchor of the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] [[television program]] ''[[Nightly Business Report]]'', a role he held from 1979, when the show was a local PBS program in Miami, through December 31, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stelter |first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Stelter |title=Co-Anchor Is Leaving PBS Program on Business |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/07/business/media/07pbs.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=B3 |date=May 6, 2009}}</ref> He was known for signing off each NBR broadcast with "I'm Paul Kangas, wishing all of you the best of good buys" (a pun on "the best of goodbyes").
==Career== After graduating from the [[University of Michigan]], Kangas entered the [[United States Coast Guard]] in the early 1960s and served aboard the [[USCGC Mackinaw (WAGB-83)|USCG Cutter ''Mackinaw'']].{{citation needed|date=August 2009}} Later, he served as aide to the admiral in command of the [[Organization of the United States Coast Guard#Regional responsibilities|9th Coast Guard District]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].{{citation needed|date=August 2009}} Kangas completed his Coast Guard service in 1963 as a [[Lieutenant (junior grade)]].
Kangas earned his broker's license after studying at the [[New York University Stern School of Business]].<ref name="about">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/nbr/site/about/bio/kangas/ |title=Paul Kangas Biography |website=[[Nightly Business Report]] |accessdate=March 3, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604132026/http://www.pbs.org/nbr/site/about/bio/kangas/ |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |dead-url=unfit}}</ref> While a stock broker, Kangas began his career as a broadcaster at [[WINZ (AM)|WINZ]], a [[CBS Radio]] affiliate in Miami owned by his biggest client.<ref name="about"/>
Kangas joined ''Nightly Business Report'' in 1979; in 2003, his "Stocks in the News" segment earned a Financial Writers and Editors Award from the [[Medill School of Journalism]] at Northwestern University.<ref name="about"/> He retired as co-anchor of the ''Nightly Business Report'' at the end of 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/06/co-anchor-of-nightly-business-report-to-depart/ |title=Co-Anchor of 'Nightly Business Report' to Depart |last=Stelter |first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Stelter |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 6, 2009}}</ref>
==Personal life== Kangas was of [[Finnish Americans|Finnish]] descent, and an amateur radio operator with the callsign W4LAA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/european/FinnsAmer/finchro.html |title=The Finns in America |first=Taru |last=Spiegel |website=[[Library of Congress]] |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://wireless2.fcc.gov/UlsApp/UlsSearch/license.jsp?licKey=797975 |title= ULS License - Amateur License - W4LAA - KANGAS, PAUL H |website=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> He died on February 28, 2017 in Miami, Florida from complications of [[Parkinson's disease]] and [[prostate cancer]], aged 79.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/02/business/paul-kangas-dead.html?_r=0 |title=Paul Kangas, 79, Anchor Who Brought Stocks Into Living Rooms, Dies |first=Patricia |last=Cohen |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=B12 |date=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cohen |first=Howard |title='Nightly Business Report' anchor Paul Kangas dies at 79 |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/obituaries/article135764688.html |newspaper=[[Miami Herald]] |date=March 2, 2017}}</ref>
==Awards and honors== *In 2005, Kangas won a [[Suncoast Chapter]] [[Suncoast Chapter#Silver Circle Awards|Silver Circle Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suncoastchapter.org/silver/SilverCircle2005.htm |title=Six Great Guys Receive the 2005 Silver Circle Award |website=[[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=March 3, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322020044/http://www.suncoastchapter.org/silver/SilverCircle2005.htm |archivedate=March 22, 2012 |dead-url=unfit}}</ref>
*The [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] presented the 2009 Lifetime Achievement Award in Business & Financial Reporting to Paul Kangas and Linda O'Bryon, the latter the founder of NBR and now chief content officer of Northern California Public Broadcasting.<ref>{{cite web |title= Emmy® Winners Announced For Business & Financial Reporting And Promotional Announcements |url=http://emmyonline.org/mediacenter/business_7th_winners.html |website=[[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] |date=December 7, 2009 |access-date= March 2, 2017}}</ref>
